Such verses, originally sung or re- cited in the Tuscan and Latin villages at nuptials or religious festivals, were first introduced at Rome by Histriam, who were summoned from Etruria to Rome in order to allay a pestilence which was depopulating the city. (Liv. vii. 2.) These Histrions‚ being mounted on a stage, like our mountebanks, perfomied a sort of ballet, by dancing and gesticu- lating to the sound of musical instrumenta. The Roman youths thus learned to imitate their gestures and music, which they accompanied with railing verses delivered in extemporary dialogue. Such verses were tex-med Fescennine, either because they were invented at F escetznia, a city of Etruria ; or from Fascinus, one of the Roman deities.
